- A ticket with a longer response time and more updates may indicate higher complexity or more urgent issues.;
- The `is_parent` flag is used to identify parent tickets in the hierarchy.;
- The `requester_id` links to the `requesters` table to fetch additional information about the requester.;
- The `group_id` links to the `groups` table to fetch information about the group handling the ticket.

- A "parent ticket" is a ticket that can have one or more child tickets associated with it;
- "Child tickets" are tickets that are created as sub-tickets under a parent ticket;
- "Hierarchy" in this context refers to the structure where tickets can have parent-child relationships;
- "Performance metrics" include the average resolution time and satisfaction rating for tickets handled by each group.

- High-priority tickets are those with a priority level of 1;
- The IT department is one of the departments in the organization;
- The most active requester is the one who has submitted the highest number of tickets.

- "average resolution time" refers to the mean time taken to resolve tickets in each group;
- "average response time" refers to the mean time taken to respond to tickets in each group;
- "top 5 groups" are those with the highest average resolution times;
- "longest time to resolve tickets" is a metaphor for groups that have the highest average resolution times;
- "slowest runners in a race" is a metaphor for groups that take the longest to resolve tickets.

- `resolution_time` is the duration it takes to fully resolve a ticket;
- `response_time` is the time it takes to first respond to a ticket;
- `satisfaction_rating` is a measure of how satisfied the customer is with the service provided.

- "Tapestry of customer service metrics" refers to the combination of average resolution times and satisfaction ratings;
- "Types of issues" include various categories such as technical, billing, etc.;
- "Departments" refer to different sections within the organization that handle customer tickets.

